  "why": "The paper proposes a dual-model fuzzing framework, TWINFUZZ, which uses a resistant and a vulnerable model to find 'edge samples' through 'agreement mining'. These generated samples are then used to fine-tune the resistant model to improve its robustness. The entire experimental evaluation focuses on measuring the improved robust accuracy of this single, fine-tuned model. The paper does not demonstrate or evaluate whether the adversarial examples discovered during the fuzzing process can cause failures in other, independent models that were not part of the fuzzing framework. The concept of 'generalized robustness' explored in the paper refers to robustness against unseen attack *types* (cross-attack validation) or unseen data *domains*, not unseen model architectures. Therefore, the paper does not demonstrate cross-model transferability of the discovered failures.",
